#==================================================================================================#
# Ванаминго в Реддинге
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{1}{The sheriff asked you to deal with the widow Rooney. She has locked herself in her house and has refused to come outside for a whole week.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{2}{Rooney is afraid of the wanamingos. According to her, the wanamingos walk around the house at night, jump on the roof, and try to get inside. }
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{3}{The sheriff has been informed that lately Rooney has been hearing strange sounds at night. Their nature could not be determined, but the widow insists they are wanamingos. The sheriff advised questioning Miss Majesku.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{4}{You told Rooney that Josh Lawrence had been frightening her. Rooney recalled a time when Josh Lawrence proposed that she move in with him. She rejected his offer. Realizing that Josh pulled the wanamingo pranks out of love for her, hoping she would get scared and change her mind, Rooney asked you not to tell the sheriff about it.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{5}{Miss Majesku heard strange sounds but paid them little attention, thinking it was just the wind. She recalls that long ago the wanamingos dug up graves in the town cemetery and got loose. She sincerely fears that history is repeating itself and asks you to find out what is going on. You should question Josh Lawrence, owner of the "Last Gasp" saloon, perhaps he has heard something about the wanamingos.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{6}{The sheriff has been informed of the noises Miss Majesku is hearing.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{7}{A conversation with Josh Lawrence in the "Last Gasp" saloon. He said that at night something rustles in the cemetery, with terrible growls, suspicious squeaks, and other sounds. He points to the dug-up graves and suggests it is the work of wanamingo claws.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{8}{The sheriff has been informed of the conversation with Lawrence. The sheriff asked you to question the local doctor.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{9}{The doctor is skeptical that even a single wanamingo could have survived, and says the creatures vanished long ago, that Lawrence likes to embellish, and recommends talking to the children in the streets, maybe they know something.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{10}{Keep questioning the children.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{11}{Keep questioning the children.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{12}{Keep questioning the children.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{13}{Keep questioning the children.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{14}{Keep questioning the children.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{15}{A child saw Lawrence near Rooney's house at night, holding a huge rock on a rope. He would throw the rock onto the roof and rattle it across the slate.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{16}{The sheriff has been informed of the child's account of Lawrence's nighttime activities.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{17}{Lawrence confessed that he had been frightening the widow Rooney at night. He wanted to scare her so that, afraid to live alone, she would finally accept his offer and move in with him.}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{18}{You carried out the sheriff's task of dealing with Rooney.}

{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{QName}{Redding}
{CritterProperty::ReddMarionVinamingo}{QDesc}{Wanamingos in Redding}
